<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-581-956  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 581 956.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  August 17 1989 v15 n17 p9(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Analyst questions worth of computer security measures. (securityanalyst Harold Highland disputes security claims)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Weinberg, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer security matters are the top concern of a panel ofexperts at the seventh annual PC Expo in New York City.andP;  A PCSecurity panel featuring COMPUTERS andamp; SECURITY editor HaroldHighland pointed out that, while mainframes were designed withlimited access in mind, open access is a basic component ofmicrocomputers.andP;  This fundamental component makes the prospect ofsecurity dubious in large organizations where thousands ofcomputers are networked.andP;  Computer security products such asencryption devices are liable to be ineffective where employeeswith access to security codes are concerned.andP;  Panel members agreedthat only a small proportion of computer crime is reported topolice in the US.andP;  Such disclosure is often viewed as undesirableby image-conscious executives.andP;  Ultimately, the panel concluded,ethics and workforce loyalty are the best form of protectionagainst computer crime.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     PC ExpoComputer IndustryConferences and MeetingsSecuritySystem Integrity.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Harold Highland. (portrait)Person:    Highland, Harold (addresses, essays, lectures).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>